rvive%20to%20this%20day.%20He%20died%20in%202005%2C%20at%20the%20age%20of%2092%2C%20a%20dedicated%20peace%20activist%20who%20shared%20his%20story%20with%20people%20around%20the%20globe%2C%20including%20before%20the%20UN%20General%20Assembly.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F06143459%2F24916c87-4d7b-4ee3-9faf-226395cc1115_3600x3600.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F06143459%2F24916c87-4d7b-4ee3-9faf-226395cc1115_3600x3600.jpg%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F06143459%2F24916c87-4d7b-4ee3-9faf-226395cc1115_3600x3600-300x300.jpg%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F06143459%2F24916c87-4d7b-4ee3-9faf-226395cc1115_3600x3600-1024x1024.jpg%201024w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F06143459%2F24916c87-4d7b-4ee3-9faf-226395cc1115_3600x3600-150x150.jpg%20150w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-666886%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EWest%20end%20of%20Miyuki%20Bridge%20in%20Hiroshima%2C%20morning%20of%20Aug.%206%2C%201945.%20This%20was%20taken%20moving%20in%20closer%20after%20the%20photo%20above%2C%20explained%20Yoshito%20Matsushige.%20That%20evening%20the%20injured%20were%20taken%20by%20truck%20to%20Ujina%20and%20Ninoshima%20Island.%20Photo%3A%20Yoshito%20Matsushige%2C%20Chugoku%20Shimbun.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EChristopher%20Nolan%20has%20said%20his%20film%20%E2%80%93%20which%20was%20inspired%20by%20Kai%20Bird%20and%20Martin%20J.%20Sherwin%E2%80%99s%20Pulitzer%20Prize-winning%20biography%20of%20Oppenheimer%2C%20%3Cem%3EAmerican%20Prometheus%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0is%20focused%20more%20on%20the%20moral%20dilemmas%20facing%20the%20scientist%20tasked%20with%20making%20a%20bomb%20that%20could%20end%20World%20War%20II%20than%20on%20making%20a%20war%20%E2%80%9Cdocumentary.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CHe%20%5BOppenheimer%5D%20learned%20about%20the%20bombings%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20on%20the%20radio%E2%80%94the%20same%20as%20the%20rest%20of%20the%20world%2C%E2%80%9D%20Nolan%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%20noreferrer%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Flink.sbstck.com%2Fredirect%2F670c3004-a64a-44ec-9b33-677733309726%3Fj%3DeyJ1IjoiMWc3ZDkifQ.ANHu2vRAyuFpjv7uiZBbU4uAYv19NWdGMb8wTAqqIz8%5C%22%20data-saferedirecturl%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Furl%3Fq%3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Flink.sbstck.com%2Fredirect%2F670c3004-a64a-44ec-9b33-677733309726%3Fj%253DeyJ1IjoiMWc3ZDkifQ.ANHu2vRAyuFpjv7uiZBbU4uAYv19NWdGMb8wTAqqIz8%26amp%3Bsource%3Dgmail%26amp%3Bust%3D1691324077535000%26amp%3Busg%3DAOvVaw2lwDnDcNf7d2IBP68Oowz1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etold%3C%2Fa%3E%20MSNBC%E2%80%99s%20Chuck%20Todd.%20%E2%80%9CThat%2C%20to%20me%2C%20was%20a%20shock%E2%80%A6%20Everything%20is%20%3Cem%3Ehis%3C%2Fem%3E%20experience%2C%20or%20my%20interpretation%20of%20his%20experience.%20Because%20as%20I%20keep%20reminding%20everyone%2C%20it%E2%80%99s%20not%20a%20documentary.%20It%20is%20an%20interpretation.%20That%E2%80%99s%20my%20job.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFair%20enough.%20But%20I%20can%E2%80%99t%20help%20thinking%20of%20the%20photographer%20Matsushige%20and%20what%20he%20told%20me%20over%20a%20quarter-century%20ago%2C%20while%20taking%20pictures%20of%20children%20whose%20clothes%20and%20skin%20were%20charred%20and%20hanging%20from%20their%20bodies%20when%20only%20a%20few%20moments%20prior%20they%20were%20walking%20to%20school%20on%20a%20clear%20August%20morning%3A%20%E2%80%9CI%20just%20took%20a%20picture%20of%20you%20as%20you%20are%20suffering%2C%20but%20this%20is%20my%20duty.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBelow%20is%20an%20interview%2C%20also%20from%201995%2C%20with%20the%20then-mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%2C%20Takashi%20Hiraoka%2C%20who%2C%20coincidentally%2C%20was%20a%20journalist%20before%20entering%20politics%20and%20worked%20for%20the%20same%20newspaper%20as%20Matsushige%2C%20the%20%3Cem%3EChugoku%20Shimbun%3C%2Fem%3E.%20I%20remember%20him%20as%20a%20true%20gentleman%20in%20his%20mid-60s%2C%20at%20ease%20with%20his%20role%20in%20local%20politics%20and%20passionate%20about%20sharing%20Hiroshima%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9CNever%20Again%E2%80%9D%20message%20with%20the%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENow%2095%2C%20Hiraoka%20served%20eight%20years%20as%20mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%20before%20retiring%20in%201998.%20Since%20our%20interview%2C%20two%20more%20countries%20%E2%80%93%20Pakistan%20and%20North%20Korea%20%E2%80%93%20have%20joined%20the%20nine-member%20%E2%80%9Cnuclear%20club.%E2%80%9D%20According%20to%20the%20Stockholm%20International%20Peace%20Research%20Institute%2C%20the%20US%2C%20the%20UK%2C%20Russia%2C%20France%2C%20China%2C%20India%2C%20Pakistan%2C%20Israel%2C%20and%20North%20Korea%20have%20among%20them%20nearly%2016%2C000%20nuclear%20weapons%2C%20all%20of%20which%20are%20many%20times%20more%20powerful%20than%20the%20two%20bombs%20dropped%20on%20Japan%20in%20August%201945.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%C2%A7%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EExcerpts%20from%20the%201995%C2%A0%20interview%20of%20the%20then-mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%2C%20Takashi%20Hiraoka%2C%20as%20published%20by%20%3C%2Fem%3EThe%20Japan%20Times%20Weekly%2C%3Cem%3E%20August%205%2C%201995.%20Used%20with%20the%20author%E2%80%99s%20permission%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EMJ%3A%20As%20mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%2C%20what%20is%20your%20message%20to%20the%20world%20on%20the%2050th%20anniversary%20of%20the%20atomic%20bombing%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETH%3A%20The%20atomic%20bombings%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20marked%20not%20only%20the%20end%20of%20World%20War%20II%20but%20the%20beginning%20of%20the%20nuclear%20age.%20In%20this%20respect%2C%20the%20bombings%20were%20a%20tragedy%20for%20all%20of%20humanity.%20The%20people%20of%20Hiroshima%20have%20chosen%20to%20see%20their%20experience%20as%20a%20lesson%20for%20humanity.%20The%2050th%20anniversary%20of%20the%20atomic%20bombing%20of%20Hiroshima%20is%20an%20excellent%20opportunity%20for%20us%20to%20look%20back%20on%20our%20past%20and%20think%20about%20our%20future.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOur%20message%20has%20always%20been%20that%20the%20tragedies%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20should%20never%20be%20repeated.%20Now%20that%20we%20have%20reached%20the%20half-century%20landmark%2C%20this%20message%20should%20be%20re-emphasized%2C%20together%20with%20the%20call%20for%20nuclear%20disarmament.%20I%20see%20the%2050th%20anniversary%20as%20an%20opportunity%20to%20come%20together%20with%20the%20people%20of%20the%20world%20so%20that%20we%20can%20work%20toward%20the%20abolition%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EJapan%20does%20not%20consider%20the%20use%20of%20nuclear%20weapons%20to%20be%20against%20international%20law.%20What%20is%20Hiroshima%E2%80%99s%20official%20stance%20on%20the%20deployment%20of%20nuclear%20weapons%20%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAs%20the%20first%20city%20to%20have%20experienced%20a%20nuclear%20attack%2C%20we%20firmly%20believe%20that%20the%20use%20of%20nuclear%20weapons%20violates%20international%20law.%20We%20believe%20this%20for%20two%20main%20reasons.%20The%20first%20is%20the%20indiscriminate%20nature%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%20It%20is%20extremely%20difficult%2C%20if%20not%20impossible%2C%20to%20restrict%20the%20destructive%20power%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%20The%20second%20reason%20is%20the%20extraordinary%20cruelty%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%20What%20I%20mean%20by%20this%20is%20that%20there%20are%20still%20many%20hibakusha%20(atomic%20bomb%20survivors)%20suffering%20the%20effects%20of%20radiation%20exposure.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInternational%20law%20prohibits%20the%20deployment%20of%20weapons%20that%20inflict%20unnecessary%20suffering%20on%20human%20beings%20such%20as%20%E2%80%9Cdumdum%E2%80%9D%20bullets%20and%20chemical%20weapons.%20The%20United%20Nations%20General%20Assembly%20has%20passed%20a%20number%20of%20resolutions%20prohibiting%20the%20use%20of%20nuclear%20weapons%20for%20the%20very%20same%20reason.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Japanese%20government%20has%20three%20non-nuclear%20principles%3A%20not%20to%20produce%2C%20possess%2C%20or%20harbour%20nuclear%20weapons.%20We%20must%20continue%20to%20push%20the%20government%20to%20uphold%20these%20three%20principles.%20Unfortunately%2C%20the%20Japanese%20government%20does%20not%20have%20a%20strong%20stance%20toward%20U.S.%20foreign%20policy%20because%20it%20wants%20to%20maintain%20good%20U.S.-Japan%20relations.%20But%20I%20think%20the%20Japanese%20government%20should%20have%20a%20stronger%20stance%20toward%20the%20United%20States%2C%20particularly%20in%20regard%20to%20its%20nuclear-weapons%20policy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EIn%20what%20ways%20does%20the%20city%20of%20Hiroshima%20influence%20the%20governments%20of%20other%20nations%3F%20How%20do%20you%20get%20your%20message%20across%20to%20the%20world%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhenever%20a%20foreign%20country%20conducts%20a%20nuclear-weapons%20test%2C%20we%20immediately%20send%20a%20telegram%20protesting%20the%20test%20and%20calling%20for%20an%20end%20to%20further%20nuclear-weapons%20testing.%20We%20also%20have%20a%20program%20called%20the%20International%20Conference%20of%20Mayors%20for%20Peace%20Through%20Inter-city%20Solidarity.%20Currently%2C%20404%20cities%20in%2097%20countries%20are%20a%20part%20of%20the%20program%20and%20support%20our%20call%20for%20the%20total%20abolition%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%20The%20purpose%20of%20the%20program%20is%20to%20contribute%20to%20lasting%20world%20peace%20by%20strengthening%20the%20ties%20between%20the%20cities%20of%20the%20world%E2%80%A6%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EHiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20have%20long%20been%20calling%20for%20the%20total%20abolition%20of%20nuclear%20weapons.%20How%20can%20this%20goal%20be%20attained%20when%20many%20countries%E2%80%94Iran%20and%20North%20Korea%2C%20for%20example%E2%80%94see%20having%20a%20nuclear-weapons%20program%20as%20the%20key%20to%20gaining%20respect%20on%20the%20world%20stage%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20a%20very%20difficult%20problem%2C%20and%20one%20the%20whole%20world%20will%20have%20to%20work%20on%20together%20to%20solve.%20We%20must%20continue%20to%20tell%20the%20citizens%20and%20leaders%20of%20the%20world%20that%20possessing%20nuclear%20weapons%20will%20never%20be%20a%20positive%20thing.%20Governments%20justify%20their%20nuclear%20arsenals%20with%20language%20like%20%E2%80%9Cnational%20security.%E2%80%9D%20But%20what%20about%20global%20security%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENot%20only%20does%20nuclear%20war%20mean%20the%20annihilation%20of%20humans%2C%20but%20every%20time%20a%20nuclear%20weapon%20is%20tested%2C%20the%20environment%20is%20irreparably%20damaged.%20What%20we%20have%20to%20do%20is%20raise%20public%20awareness%20of%20the%20dangers.%20We%20can%20push%20for%20the%20ratification%20of%20the%20Comprehensive%20Test%20Ban%20Treaty%20as%20soon%20as%20the%20negotiations%20are%20completed%20next%20year%E2%80%A6%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%5BApart%20from%20the%20Comprehensive%20Test%20Ban%20Treaty%5D%20%E2%80%A6%20we%20must%20also%20enact%20a%20law%20or%20treaty%20that%20ensures%20nations%20which%20possess%20nuclear%20weapons%20will%20never%20use%20them%20against%20nations%20that%20do%20not.%20Such%20a%20treaty%20will%20ease%20the%20concern%20of%20nations%20that%20do%20not%20have%20nuclear%20weapons%20and%2C%20hopefully%2C%20lessen%20the%20incentive%20to%20initiate%20a%20nuclear-weapons%20program.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20must%20also%20have%20strict%20control%20over%20the%20materials%20required%20to%20produce%20nuclear%20weapons.%20Those%20countries%20currently%20trying%20to%20develop%20nuclear%20weapons%20feel%20they%20are%20not%20given%20equal%20consideration%20in%20international%20politics.%20So%2C%20on%20the%20one%20hand%2C%20we%20need%20strict%20control%20over%20nuclear%20materials%2C%20and%20on%20the%20other%20we%20have%20to%20address%20the%20needs%20and%20concerns%20of%20all%20the%20nations%20of%20the%20world%20in%20equal%20measure.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EIn%20the%20United%20States%20and%20Japan%2C%20there%20was%20a%20great%20deal%20of%20controversy%20over%20a%20commemorative%20stamp%20that%20was%20to%20be%20issued%20by%20the%20U.S.%20Postal%20Service.%20The%20stamp%2C%20which%20was%20never%20issued%2C%20featured%20a%20painting%20of%20an%20atomic%20mushroom%20cloud%20accompanied%20by%20the%20caption%20%E2%80%9CAtomic%20bombs%20hasten%20war%E2%80%99s%20end%2C%20August%201945.%E2%80%9D%20What%20kind%20of%20message%20do%20you%20think%20it%20sends%20the%20people%20around%20the%20world%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20have%20many%20reasons%20to%20believe%20that%20the%20statement%20%E2%80%9CAtomic%20bombs%20hasten%20war%E2%80%99s%20end%E2%80%9D%20is%20simply%20not%20true.%20By%20August%201945%2C%20Japan%20had%20neither%20the%20ability%20nor%20the%20will%20to%20continue%20waging%20war.%20The%20Japanese%20government%20was%20trying%20to%20find%20a%20path%20to%20peace%20as%20early%20as%20the%20spring%20of%201945.%20I%20believe%20the%20U.S.%20government%20was%20aware%20of%20this%20when%20it%20decided%20to%20drop%20the%20atomic%20bomb.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIf%20the%20United%20States%20had%20wanted%20only%20to%20end%20the%20war%2C%20it%20did%20not%20have%20to%20use%20nuclear%20weapons.%20The%20United%20States%20possessed%20more%20than%20enough%20conventional%20weapons%20to%20destroy%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20and%20to%20end%20the%20war.%20There%20are%20many%20different%20opinions%20as%20to%20why%20the%20U.S.%20government%20decided%20to%20drop%20atomic%20bombs%20on%20the%20cities%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20would%20like%20to%20leave%20the%20answer%20to%20the%20scholars%2C%20but%20I%20do%20have%20a%20question.%20In%201945%2C%20President%20Harry%20Truman%20said%20that%20dropping%20the%20atomic%20bombs%20saved%20250%2C000%20to%20500%2C000%20lives.%20In%201985%2C%20President%20Ronald%20Reagan%20said%20dropping%20the%20atomic%20bombs%20saved%20one%20million%20American%20soldiers%E2%80%99%20lives.%20In%201991%2C%20President%20George%20Bush%20said%20that%20several%20million%20lives%20were%20saved%20as%20a%20result%20of%20the%20atomic%20bombings.%20I%20wonder%20what%20this%20change%20means%3F%20I%20understand%20that%20the%20U.S.%20government%20uses%20these%20figures%20to%20justify%20the%20bombings%2C%20and%20that%20once%20a%20government%20has%20committed%20itself%20to%20a%20certain%20policy%20or%20decision%2C%20it%20does%20not%20want%20to%20change%20its%20stand.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20why%20do%20the%20numbers%20keep%20rising%3F%20Before%20the%20atomic%20bombs%20were%20dropped%2C%20many%20U.S.%20officials%2C%20including%20military%20personnel%2C%20argued%20that%20the%20bombings%20were%20not%20needed%20to%20end%20the%20war.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20is%20your%20reaction%20to%20the%20Smithsonian%20Institution%E2%80%99s%20decision%20to%20scale%20back%20its%20controversial%20Enola%20Gay%20exhibit%20at%20the%20National%20Air%20and%20Space%20Museum%20in%20Washington%20D.C.%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20couple%20of%20years%20ago%20the%20Smithsonian%20Institution%20had%20an%20extensive%20exhibition%20on%20World%20War%20II%20that%20included%20an%20exhibit%20on%20the%20plight%20of%20the%20Japanese%20Americans%20who%20were%20interned%20during%20the%20war.%20Due%20in%20part%20to%20this%20exhibit%2C%20the%20U.S.%20government%20admitted%20that%20its%20policy%20was%20a%20mistake%20and%20compensated%20the%20surviving%20Japanese%20Americans%20who%20had%20been%20interned.%20This%20led%20me%20to%20believe%20that%20the%20people%20at%20the%20Smithsonian%20Institution%20were%20committed%20to%20historical%20accuracy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENow%2C%20the%20Smithsonian%20has%20yielded%20to%20political%20pressure%20and%20has%20missed%20an%20opportunity%20to%20thoroughly%20examine%20the%20history%20surrounding%20the%20bombings.%20I%20am%20disappointed%20with%20the%20Smithsonian%E2%80%99s%20decision%2C%20as%20are%20many%20people%20of%20conscience%20in%20this%20world.%20We%20could%20spend%20hours%20talking%20about%20whether%20the%20atomic%20bombings%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20were%20justifiable%20or%20not%2C%20but%20such%20discussion%20is%20futile%E2%80%94it%20happened%2050%20years%20ago.%20What%20we%20have%20to%20do%20now%20is%20learn%20from%20the%20experience%20and%20make%20sure%20it%20never%20happens%20again.%20We%20are%20not%20asking%20for%20an%20apology.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESome%20Americans%20say%20that%20we%20are%20trying%20to%20make%20ourselves%20look%20like%20innocent%20victims%2C%20that%20we%20are%20indulging%20in%20our%20grief%20in%20an%20attempt%20to%20diminish%20the%20atrocities%20committed%20by%20the%20Japanese%20military%20during%20the%20war.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENothing%20could%20be%20further%20from%20the%20truth.%20As%20the%20mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%20I%20acknowledge%20that%20the%20Japanese%20military%20carried%20out%20a%20war%20of%20aggression%20and%20committed%20many%20atrocities.%20I%20have%20personally%20done%20a%20lot%20of%20soul-searching%20on%20this%20subject%20and%20have%20publicly%20apologized%20to%20those%20who%20suffered%20at%20the%20hands%20of%20the%20Japanese%20military.%20I%20would%20also%20like%20to%20add%20that%20if%20nuclear%20weapons%20are%20not%20abolished%2C%20the%20horrors%20that%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki%20experienced%20will%20be%20experienced%20by%20others.%20The%20question%20is%20not%20if%20but%20when%20it%20will%20happen.%20The%20nuclear%20weapons%20that%20exist%20today%20are%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20times%20more%20powerful%20than%20the%20atomic%20bombs%20dropped%20on%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki.%20Obviously%2C%20a%20tragedy%20brought%20about%20by%20a%20nuclear%20war%20today%20would%20be%20far%20greater%20than%20the%20tragedies%20of%20Hiroshima%20and%20Nagasaki.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhy%20do%20you%20think%20the%20Smithsonian%20Institution%20decided%20against%20displaying%20photographs%20of%20and%20items%20belonging%20to%20the%20victims%20of%20the%20bombings%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20seems%20many%20Americans%20are%20not%20willing%20to%20face%20the%20reality%20of%20what%20happened%20after%20the%20bomb%20was%20released%2C%20but%20for%20humanity%20that%20is%20where%20the%20lesson%20begins.%20Hiroshima%E2%80%99s%20mission%20is%20to%20let%20the%20people%20of%20the%20world%20know%20what%20happened%20on%20the%20ground%E2%80%94what%20happened%20to%20the%20people%20of%20our%20city.%20I%20first%20came%20to%20Hiroshima%20in%20September%201945%2C%20so%20I%20remember%20very%20well%20the%20devastation%20and%20the%20initial%20rebuilding%20of%20the%20city.%20What%20moved%20me%20most%20was%20the%20strength%20of%20the%20survivors.%20That%20strength%20has%20evolved%20into%20a%20determination%20to%20prevent%20others%20from%20experiencing%20the%20horrors%20of%20nuclear%20war.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThey%20feel%20it%20is%20their%20duty%20to%20make%20a%20constant%20appeal%20for%20world%20peace%20and%20nuclear%20disarmament.%20This%20is%20their%20mission%2C%20and%20with%20this%20mission%20they%20have%20overcome%20their%20tragedy.%20They%20do%20not%20harbor%20any%20hatred%20toward%20the%20American%20people.%20Instead%2C%20they%20have%20chosen%20to%20work%20for%20peace.%20The%20people%20of%20Hiroshima%20have%20come%20to%20understand%20what%20peace%20means%20for%20the%20world.%20And%20as%20the%20mayor%20of%20Hiroshima%2C%20I%20am%20very%20proud%20of%20them.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EA%20version%20of%20this%20article%20was%20originally%20published%20on%20the%20author%E2%80%99s%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%20noreferrer%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22ht